ed Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Haydock","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Haddock   1 and 2.","Americanized form of Czech or Polish   Hejduk  , Polish, Slovak, Rusyn (from Slovakia and Poland), or Czech   Hajduk  , and of their Hungarian cognate <b>Hajdók</b>. Compare   Hydock  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Haddock","meanings":["English:","variant of the Lancashire surname   Haydock  , a habitational name from a place so called near Liverpool, which is probably named from Welsh <i>heiddog</i> ‘characterized by barley’.","from the Middle English personal name <i>Addoc</i>, a pet form of Old English <i>Æddi</i> (itself perhaps derived from one of the names in <i>ēad</i> ‘wealth, prosperity’), with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"III","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Japanese Yuko, Aiko, Hideaki, Hiroki, Hiroyuki, Isamu, Kaoru, Katsumi, Keiichiro, Kenji, Masako, Masayuki.","Japanese: variously written, sometimes with characters used phonetically; the most probable meanings are 仁井 ‘benevolent well’, 新居 ‘new residence’, or 新井 ‘new well’. It is not common in Japan."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Gilbert III de Haydock was born in 1290, in Warrington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Gilbert de Haydock II. He married Emma de Houghton in 1319, in Haydock, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died before 1362, in Haydock, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1290–Bef 1362":"1290–enne 1362","1290–1362":"1290–1362","1304–1332":"1304–1332","1322–1387":"1322–1387","1322–1390":"1322–1390","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","Bef 1362":"enne 1362","1304":"1304","1322":"1322","1332":"1332","1387":"1387","1362":"1362","1250":"1250","1319":"1319","1390":"1390","1290":"1290","Haydock, Lancashire, England":"Haydock, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Warrington, Lancashire, England":"Warrington, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1290–Bef 1362":"1290–ennen vuotta 1362","1290–1362":"1290–1362","1304–1332":"1304–1332","1322–1387":"1322–1387","1322–1390":"1322–1390","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","Bef 1362":"ennen vuotta 1362","1304":"1304","1322":"1322","1332":"1332","1387":"1387","1362":"1362","1250":"1250","1319":"1319","1390":"1390","1290":"1290","Haydock, Lancashire, England":"Haydock, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Warrington, Lancashire, England":"Warrington, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1